      <hedline>
        <hl1>Alaska</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harry and Lois Petersen letter on August 20 article on cruising Alaska's Glacier Bay recalls 1972 trip (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Re: ''A Land So Wild, It's Getting Crowded'' (Aug. 20) Cruise ships in Glacier Bay -- horrors! Our Alaska adventure was in 1972 -- prepipeline. We flew to Juneau with our girls, then to Glacier Bay, to a government-run hotel. A small government boat took us for our best day, all along the quiet bay, with the whales, seals and birds of all varieties.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Re: ''A Land So Wild, It's Getting Crowded'' (Aug. 20) Cruise ships in Glacier Bay -- horrors! Our Alaska adventure was in 1972 -- prepipeline. We flew to Juneau with our girls, then to Glacier Bay, to a government-run hotel. A small government boat took us for our best day, all along the quiet bay, with the whales, seals and birds of all varieties.</p>
        <p>We flew to Anchorage (one hotel), then drove to Mount McKinley National Park (government-run hotel again) and spent a day going to the mountain with a ranger -- bears, moose, sheep in abundance. Then  we drove to the Kenai Peninsula (Routes 1, 2, and 3 uncrowded -- no tour buses). We're glad we saw Alaska then; it was a fabulous state!</p>
        <p>HARRY PETERSEN  LOIS PETERSEN  New York, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
